#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:1
msgid "Chapter 32. Constructing a VM and Running a Module"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will understand each phase of VM construction "
"and the lifetime relationship between the VM and the arena."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:8
msgid "The four phases"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:10
msgid ""
"Constructing a VM from source is four phases, each producing a distinct type."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:14
msgid "// Vec<Token>\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:15
msgid "// Program\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:16
msgid "// Module\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:21
msgid "`tokenize` turns source text into a `Vec<Token>`."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:22
msgid "`parse` turns the tokens into a `Program`, the syntax tree."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:23
msgid "`compile` turns the program into a `Module`, the bytecode object."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:24
msgid ""
"`Vm::new` consumes the module, borrows the arena, runs structural "
"verification and resource-bounds verification, and returns a VM ready to "
"call."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:28
msgid ""
"Each phase returns a `Result`. A failure in any phase is a typed error: "
"`LexError`, `ParseError`, `CompileError`, or, from `Vm::new`, "
"`VmError::VerifyError`."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:32
msgid "Verification happens at construction"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:34
msgid ""
"`Vm::new` is where the guarantees of Part V are enforced. It runs the "
"structural verifier and the resource-bounds verifier before returning. A "
"program the verifier rejects never yields a VM; `Vm::new` returns "
"`Err(VmError::VerifyError(message))`, and the message is the one documented "
"in `WHY_REJECTED.md`. No script code has run at that point. The host learns "
"a program is unacceptable at construction, not partway through execution."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:42
msgid "The arena and its lifetime"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:44
msgid ""
"The arena is the bounded working memory the VM uses for its operand stack "
"and for dynamic strings. The host creates it and the VM borrows it."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:47
msgid ""
"The borrow is enforced by the Rust borrow checker. `Vm` carries an `'arena` "
"lifetime parameter, and the arena must outlive the VM. In practice this "
"means the arena is declared before the VM and dropped after it, which "
"ordinary block scoping gives for free:"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:54
msgid "// vm is used here; arena outlives it\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:58
msgid ""
"Chapter 35 covers how to choose the arena capacity. For now, "
"`DEFAULT_ARENA_CAPACITY`, sixty-four kilobytes, serves."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:61
msgid "Running an atomic module"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:63
msgid "Once constructed, an atomic `fn main` module is run with `call`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:67
msgid "/* use value */"
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:68
msgid "\"expected Finished, got {:?}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:72
msgid ""
"`call` takes a slice of arguments. An `fn main` that takes no parameters is "
"called with `&[]`. The atomic module runs to completion and `call` returns "
"`VmState::Finished(value)`, carrying the return value."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:76
msgid ""
"A `yield` or `loop` module does not finish on the first `call`. It returns "
"`VmState::Yielded` instead, and driving it requires the resume protocol. "
"Chapter 34 covers that. Native functions, which most real scripts need, come "
"first, in the next chapter."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:83
msgid ""
"VM construction is four phases: `tokenize`, `parse`, `compile`, `Vm::new`."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:85
msgid ""
"`Vm::new` runs verification; a rejected program fails here, before any code "
"runs."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:87
msgid "The VM borrows the arena, and the arena must outlive the VM."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:88
msgid "`call(&[])` runs an atomic module and returns `VmState::Finished`."
msgstr ""

#: src/32_constructing_a_vm.md:90
msgid "The next chapter registers the host functions a script calls."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:1
msgid "Chapter 33. Registering Native Functions"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will be able to register host functions that "
"scripts call, by both the ergonomic and the lower-level routes."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:8
msgid "What a native function is"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:10
msgid ""
"A native function is a Rust function the host registers with the VM under a "
"name. A script calls it by that name, after a `use` declaration. Native "
"functions are the bridge: the script decides what should happen, the native "
"does it. The piano roll's `host::play` is a native; the script calls it, and "
"the Rust side updates the audio voice state."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:16
msgid ""
"Native functions are registered after `Vm::new` and before the script runs."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:19
msgid "The ergonomic route: register_fn"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:21
msgid ""
"The recommended route is `register_fn`. It accepts any Rust function or "
"closure of arity zero through four whose argument and return types implement "
"the `KeleusmaType` marshalling trait, which the primitive types already do:"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:27 src/EMBEDDING.md:91
msgid "\"math::add\""
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:28 src/38_cost_models.md:51
#: src/EMBEDDING.md:92 src/EMBEDDING.md:283
msgid "\"math::sin\""
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:31
msgid ""
"Argument extraction, arity checking, and return-value wrapping are handled "
"automatically. For a function that may fail, `register_fn_fallible` accepts "
"a `Result<R, VmError>` return:"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:36 src/EMBEDDING.md:99
msgid "\"io::read_setting\""
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:37 src/GETTING_STARTED.md:125
#: src/EMBEDDING.md:100
msgid "\"{}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:41
msgid "A host struct or enum crosses the boundary by deriving `KeleusmaType`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:48
msgid "The lower-level route: register_native_closure"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:50
msgid ""
"`register_fn` cannot capture host state, because its argument is a plain "
"function shape. When a native must read or write state the host owns, use "
"`register_native_closure`. It takes a closure that receives the raw "
"`&[Value]` arguments and returns `Result<Value, VmError>`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:57
msgid "\"host::silence\""
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:61
msgid "\"expected Int, got {:?}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:68
msgid ""
"This is the route the piano roll uses for every one of its natives, because "
"each one captures the shared `Arc<Mutex<[Voice; 8]>>` voice table. The "
"closure owns its captured clone, and inspecting the raw `Value` lets the "
"native validate its arguments explicitly. A plain function pointer with no "
"captured state can instead use `register_native`."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:74
msgid "Bundled libraries"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:76
msgid ""
"The `keleusma::stddsl` module ships three bundles of natives, registered in "
"one call each:"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:80
msgid "// math::sqrt, math::pow, ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:81 src/EMBEDDING.md:195
msgid "// audio::midi_to_freq, ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:82
msgid ""
"// shell::getenv, shell::run, shell::sleep_ms,\n"
"                                      // shell::read_file, "
"shell::write_file, ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:86
msgid ""
"The Shell bundle in V0.2.1 covers environment access (`getenv`, `has_env`, "
"`setenv`), subprocess execution (`run`, `run_full`, `run_checked`, "
"`run_timeout`), process termination (`exit`), timing (`sleep_ms`, "
"`now_unix_ms`), file I/O (`read_file`, `write_file`, `append_file`, "
"`file_exists`), stderr output (`write_err`, `writeln_err`), and host "
"metadata (`pid`, `hostname`, `arg_count`, `arg`, `pwd`, `cd`). See "
"[`STANDARD_LIBRARY.md`](../spec/STANDARD_LIBRARY.md) for the full list."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:94
msgid ""
"Each bundle exposes a public `SIGNATURES` constant containing source-form "
"`use` declarations. Hosts that want compile-time type and arity validation "
"prepend the constant to the script source before parsing; the bundled "
"`keleusma-cli` does this for all three bundles. A custom bundle can "
"implement the `Library` trait and expose a parallel `SIGNATURES` constant to "
"participate in the same validation flow."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:103
msgid "A native function is a host Rust function a script calls by name."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:104
msgid ""
"`register_fn` and `register_fn_fallible` are the ergonomic route, for "
"functions whose types implement `KeleusmaType`."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:106
msgid ""
"`register_native_closure` is the route for natives that capture host state, "
"as every piano roll native does."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:108
msgid "`register_library` installs a bundled or custom set of natives."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:109
msgid ""
"A fallible native's failure is handled on the script side with the native-"
"error construct `native(args) { ok(v) => ..., error(code) => ... }`. The "
"host reports the `Word` error code by returning an error built with the "
"`KeleusmaError` derive, which maps a fieldless enum's variants to their "
"discriminants. See [Chapter 23](./23_big_numbers.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/33_registering_natives.md:115
msgid "The next chapter drives a script that yields."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:1
msgid "Chapter 34. The Coroutine Protocol from the Host Side"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will be able to drive a `yield` or `loop` "
"script from the host, and recover from a runtime error."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:8
msgid "call, resume, and VmState"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:10
msgid ""
"The host has two entry points into a VM. `call(&[Value])` starts execution. "
"`resume(Value)` continues it after a yield. Both return `Result<VmState, "
"VmError>`, where `VmState` has three variants:"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:22
msgid "The variants correspond to the three function categories of Chapter 15."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:24
msgid ""
"An atomic `fn` script runs to completion: `call` returns `Finished(value)`."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:26
msgid ""
"A `yield` script hands a value out: `call` returns `Yielded(value)`, and the "
"host calls `resume(input)` to continue."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:28
msgid ""
"A `loop` script yields every cycle and resets at the end of its body. `call` "
"returns `Yielded`, `resume` drives the next yield, and once a body completes "
"the next call returns `Reset`."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:32
msgid "The drive loop"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:34
msgid "A host drives a yielding script with a match on `VmState`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:55
msgid ""
"The piano roll's tick loop is this pattern. Once per sixteenth-note tick it "
"calls `resume` with the current tick number, the script runs one cycle and "
"yields, and the host sleeps until the next tick boundary. When the script's "
"body completes a cycle, the state is `Reset`, which is the boundary where a "
"hot swap may happen, the subject of Chapter 37."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:61
msgid "The dialogue type"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:63
msgid ""
"The value passed to `resume` and the value carried by `Yielded` are the two "
"halves of the script's dialogue, introduced in Chapter 16. The host and the "
"script must agree on these two types. The agreement is not checked by the "
"Rust compiler, because both are carried as the runtime `Value` enum; it is "
"the host author's responsibility to supply resume values of the type the "
"script expects."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:70
msgid "Error recovery"
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:72
msgid ""
"A runtime error from `call` or `resume` returns `Err(VmError)`. The VM is "
"left in an intermediate state. The host has two choices."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:75
msgid ""
"Discard the VM and reconstruct it. Constructing a new VM against the arena "
"resets the arena."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:77
msgid ""
"Call `vm.reset_after_error()`, which clears the operand stack, the call "
"frames, and the arena, while preserving the data segment."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:84 src/EMBEDDING.md:349
msgid "\"script error: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:91
msgid ""
"`VmError` enumerates the runtime conditions: `StackUnderflow`, `TypeError`, "
"`DivisionByZero`, `IndexOutOfBounds`, `FieldNotFound`, `NoMatch`, "
"`NativeError`, `InvalidBytecode`, `Trap`, `VerifyError`, and `LoadError`. Of "
"these, `VerifyError` and `LoadError` fire at construction, before any script "
"code runs; the rest fire during execution."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:99
msgid "`call` starts a VM, `resume` continues it after a yield."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:100
msgid ""
"`VmState` is `Finished`, `Yielded`, or `Reset`, matching the three function "
"categories."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:102
msgid "A host drives a yielding script with a match-and-resume loop."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:103
msgid "The dialogue types are the host's responsibility to honor."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:104
msgid "`reset_after_error` recovers a VM while preserving the data segment."
msgstr ""

#: src/34_coroutine_protocol.md:106
msgid "The next chapter sizes the arena."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:1
msgid "Chapter 35. Sizing the Arena and Reading the Bounds"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will be able to choose an arena capacity "
"deliberately rather than relying on the default."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:8
msgid "What the arena holds"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:10
msgid ""
"The arena is a single contiguous block of memory the VM borrows. The operand "
"stack grows from one end and dynamic strings grow from the other. The total "
"used during one Stream-to-Reset iteration is bounded by the worst-case "
"memory usage, the WCMU analysis of Chapter 20. The host chooses the arena's "
"capacity at construction. There are three options."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:16
msgid "Option A: the default capacity"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:18
msgid ""
"`DEFAULT_ARENA_CAPACITY` is sixty-four kilobytes, sufficient for most "
"scripts:"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:25
msgid ""
"This is the right starting point. Move to a computed or fixed size only when "
"there is a reason."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:28
msgid "Option B: compute the capacity from the module"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:30
msgid ""
"`auto_arena_capacity_for` walks a module and returns the capacity its WCMU "
"bound requires:"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:39
msgid ""
"The second argument is a slice of per-native heap attestations; pass an "
"empty slice when the script's natives do not allocate into the arena, and "
"attested values otherwise. This option sizes the arena to exactly what the "
"program needs, no more."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:44
msgid "Option C: a static buffer"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:46
msgid ""
"On an embedded target without a heap, the arena can run from a host-owned "
"buffer placed in static memory:"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:56
msgid ""
"This is the pattern for a `no_std` deployment, where the arena is a fixed "
"region of `.bss` rather than a heap allocation."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:59
msgid "When the arena is too small"
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:61
msgid ""
"If the chosen capacity is below the module's analyzed WCMU, `Vm::new` "
"returns `VmError::VerifyError`. The error is surfaced at construction, "
"before any code runs. An undersized arena is therefore not a runtime hazard. "
"It is a construction-time rejection, the same kind of rejection as any other "
"the verifier produces."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:67
msgid ""
"This is the memory budget of Chapter 20 seen from the host side. The "
"verifier proved a WCMU bound; the host must provide an arena at least that "
"large; and the check that the two agree happens at `Vm::new`."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:73
msgid "The arena is bounded working memory; its size is the host's choice."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:74
msgid ""
"`DEFAULT_ARENA_CAPACITY` is the default; `auto_arena_capacity_for` computes "
"an exact size; `Arena::from_static_buffer` runs from static memory."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:77
msgid ""
"An arena smaller than the module's WCMU is rejected at `Vm::new`, before any "
"code runs."
msgstr ""

#: src/35_arena_sizing.md:80
msgid "The next chapter loads bytecode that was compiled ahead of time."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:1
msgid "Chapter 36. Loading Precompiled and Signed Bytecode"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will be able to load precompiled bytecode, "
"load signed bytecode against a trust matrix, and understand the trust-skip "
"constructor."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:9
msgid "Loading precompiled bytecode"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:11
msgid ""
"A host with a precompiled `.kel.bin` file, produced by `keleusma compile` or "
"by a build pipeline, skips the lex, parse, and compile phases:"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:15 src/EMBEDDING.md:37 src/EMBEDDING.md:412
msgid "\"script.kel.bin\""
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:19
msgid ""
"`Vm::load_bytes` validates the wire-format framing, runs structural "
"verification, runs resource-bounds verification, and returns the VM. A "
"framing failure is `VmError::LoadError`; an analysis failure is "
"`VmError::VerifyError`. The verification is the same as for a source-"
"compiled module; loading bytecode does not skip the safety checks, only the "
"compilation."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:26
msgid "Loading signed bytecode"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:28
msgid ""
"A module compiled from a `signed` entry function carries a "
"`FLAG_REQUIRES_SIGNATURE` bit, and `Vm::load_bytes` refuses it, directing "
"the caller to the signed path. A signed module loads through "
"`Vm::load_signed_bytes`, which takes a slice of trusted public keys:"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:34 src/EMBEDDING.md:420
msgid "\"pub.bin\""
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:39
msgid ""
"The slice is the trust matrix. The module loads if its signature verifies "
"against any key in the slice. An empty slice rejects every signed module. "
"The matrix is copied onto the constructed VM, so later signed hot-swap loads "
"inherit the same keys."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:44
msgid ""
"A host that boots from an unsigned baseline and accepts only signed updates "
"afterward registers keys after construction:"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:52
msgid "The trust-skip constructor"
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:54
msgid ""
"`Vm::new_unchecked` skips the resource-bounds verification. Structural "
"verification still runs, because the execution loop depends on it for memory "
"safety."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:62
msgid ""
"It is marked `unsafe` to capture a trust contract: the caller attests that "
"the bytecode's resource bounds were verified earlier, at build time. The "
"intended use is a build pipeline that verifies once and ships bytecode that "
"need not be re-verified on every load. Using it to admit a program that "
"would fail the safe verifier is intentional misuse outside the language's "
"guarantees, and it is documented as such. The bounded-time and bounded-"
"memory guarantees of Part V hold under `Vm::new` and weaken to host "
"attestation under `Vm::new_unchecked`."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:73
msgid ""
"`Vm::load_bytes` loads a precompiled `.kel.bin`, verifying it the same as a "
"source-compiled module."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:75
msgid ""
"`Vm::load_signed_bytes` loads signed bytecode against a slice of trusted "
"public keys."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:77
msgid "`register_verifying_key` adds keys to a VM after construction."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:78
msgid ""
"`Vm::new_unchecked` skips the resource-bounds check under an explicit, "
"`unsafe` trust contract."
msgstr ""

#: src/36_loading_bytecode.md:81
msgid "The next chapter replaces a running module with a new one."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:1
msgid "Chapter 37. Hot Code Swap from the Host"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will be able to replace a running module with "
"a new one, from the host, at a reset boundary."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:8
msgid "The swap point"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:10
msgid ""
"Hot code swap is host-driven. A `loop` script does not replace itself. The "
"host replaces it, and only at one point: a `VmState::Reset`, the boundary "
"between two iterations of the loop body. At that boundary the script's "
"operand stack is empty, and the private data segment is the only live script-"
"owned state, which is what makes the swap safe. Shared data is the host-"
"owned buffer of Chapter 34, not script-owned state, so it is not part of the "
"swap."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:18
msgid ""
"The host watches for `Reset` in its drive loop and calls "
"`Vm::replace_module`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:30 src/EMBEDDING.md:395
msgid "/* ... */"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:34
msgid ""
"`replace_module` takes the new module and an initial private-data vector "
"whose length must match the new module's declared `private data` slot count; "
"pass an empty vector for a module with no private data. Shared data is not a "
"hot-swap input; it stays in the host's own buffer across the swap. After the "
"swap, the VM's coroutine state is cleared, so the new module is driven from "
"its entry point with `call`, not with `resume`."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:41
msgid "What survives a swap"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:43
msgid "Three things must be understood about what crosses a swap."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:45
msgid ""
"The dialogue type must stay stable. The new module must yield and resume the "
"same types as the old one, because the host keeps driving the conversation "
"without a break."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:48
msgid ""
"The private data segment is handed in fresh. The host may pass the old "
"values forward, re-initialize them to zero, or run migration code to fit a "
"new schema. The piano roll passes a freshly zeroed vector, so each incoming "
"song's init block runs against a clean slate."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:52
msgid ""
"Native function registrations live on the VM, not on the module, so they "
"persist across the swap. The new module sees the same natives the old one "
"did."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:56
msgid "Signed updates"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:58
msgid ""
"When a swap installs a module delivered as signed bytecode, the host uses "
"`Vm::replace_module_from_bytes`. It verifies the signature against the trust "
"matrix the VM carries, the matrix registered in Chapter 36, before "
"installing the module. A signed hot swap is the mechanism behind the multi-"
"party delivery scenario: a baseline device receives a signed update over a "
"link and installs it only if the signature checks out."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:65
msgid "The piano roll's swap"
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:67
msgid ""
"The piano roll is the worked example. Its stdin thread turns a keypress into "
"a swap request. The main loop, on the next `VmState::Reset`, calls "
"`replace_module` with the next song's module and an empty private-data "
"vector, resizes and re-zeroes the shared-data buffer for the new song, "
"resets its host-owned voice state, and calls the new module's entry point. "
"The audible song change is exactly this code path."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:76
msgid "Hot swap is host-driven and happens only at a `VmState::Reset`."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:77
msgid ""
"`replace_module` installs a new module and a fresh private data segment; the "
"new module is then driven from `call`."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:79
msgid ""
"The dialogue type must stay stable; native registrations persist; the "
"private data segment is the host's to carry, reset, or migrate, while shared "
"data stays in the host's buffer across the swap."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:82
msgid ""
"`replace_module_from_bytes` installs a signed update against the trust "
"matrix."
msgstr ""

#: src/37_hot_swap_host.md:85
msgid "The next chapter measures execution cost."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:1
msgid "Chapter 38. Calibrated WCET and Cost Models"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will understand how the worst-case execution "
"time is costed, and how a host obtains a figure calibrated to its hardware."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:9
msgid "The cost model"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:11
msgid ""
"The WCET analysis of Chapter 20 counts the work on the longest path between "
"two yields. To turn an opcode count into a cycle figure, it consults a cost "
"model: a table assigning a pipelined-cycle cost to each opcode, plus the "
"size of a value slot."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:16
msgid ""
"The runtime ships `NOMINAL_COST_MODEL`. Its costs are estimates, not "
"measurements: one cycle for data movement, two for arithmetic, three for "
"division, five for composite construction, ten for a function call. The "
"nominal model is sound for comparing two programs on one platform, but its "
"numbers are not the cycle counts of any specific processor."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:22
msgid "A measured model"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:24
msgid ""
"A host that needs WCET figures calibrated to a real deployment processor "
"uses a measured cost model. The `keleusma-bench` workspace member benchmarks "
"each opcode on a target and emits a generated `MEASURED_COST_MODEL` "
"fragment. The host includes the fragment for its target and passes the model "
"to the `_with_cost_model` variant of the WCET API:"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:32 src/EMBEDDING.md:296 src/COOKBOOK.md:435
#: src/COOKBOOK.md:444 src/COOKBOOK.md:448
msgid "\"CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR\""
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:33
msgid "\"/measured_cost_models/aarch64_apple_darwin.rs\""
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:40
msgid ""
"The `keleusma-bench` crate documents the capture workflow for generating a "
"fragment for a new target."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:43
msgid "Native function attestation"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:45
msgid ""
"The WCET and WCMU analyses cost a native function call as zero by default, "
"because the verifier cannot see inside the host's Rust code. A host that "
"needs a sound bound declares per-native costs before the analysis runs:"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:52 src/EMBEDDING.md:159 src/COOKBOOK.md:41
#: src/FAQ.md:24
msgid "\"text::upper\""
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:55
msgid ""
"The first number is the worst-case pipelined-cycle cost of the native, the "
"second is its worst-case arena heap allocation in bytes. These are the "
"host's promise. The verifier accepts the declared values without "
"independently measuring them, so the host bears responsibility for their "
"accuracy, established by measurement or by bounded analysis of the native."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:61
msgid "What the figure means"
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:63
msgid ""
"The bound the analysis produces is in pipelined cycles, a measure of work. "
"Converting it to wall-clock seconds on a deployment platform requires a "
"platform-specific factor that accounts for cache and pipeline stalls and the "
"clock period. The language guarantees the pipelined-cycle bound. The host "
"attests to the conversion factor for its hardware. This division of "
"responsibility is the same one Chapter 20 described, seen here from the "
"host's side."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:73
msgid ""
"A cost model assigns pipelined-cycle costs to opcodes; the analysis uses it "
"to produce a WCET figure."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:75
msgid ""
"`NOMINAL_COST_MODEL` is unmeasured and good for relative comparison; a "
"`MEASURED_COST_MODEL` from `keleusma-bench` is calibrated to a target."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:77
msgid ""
"`set_native_bounds` attests the cost of a native function so the analysis "
"can account for it."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:79
msgid ""
"The bound is in pipelined cycles; converting to wall-clock time is the "
"host's responsibility."
msgstr ""

#: src/38_cost_models.md:82
msgid "The next chapter walks a complete host end to end."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:1
msgid "Chapter 39. A Full Host, End to End"
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:5
msgid ""
"By the end of this chapter you will be able to read the complete piano roll "
"host and see where each technique from this part appears in it."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:8
msgid "The file"
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:10
msgid ""
"The piano roll host is the single file `examples/piano_roll.rs` in the "
"repository. It is around thirteen hundred lines, and it is written to be "
"read. This chapter is a map of it."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:14
msgid "Two kinds of code"
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:16
msgid ""
"The most useful thing to recognize on a first read is that the file contains "
"two kinds of code, and only one of them is about embedding Keleusma."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:20
msgid ""
"The embedding code is the subject of this part. It is a small fraction of "
"the file:"
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:23
msgid ""
"`build_module` runs `tokenize`, `parse`, and `compile`, the phases of "
"Chapter 32."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:25
msgid "`run` constructs the `Arena` and the `Vm`, the rest of Chapter 32."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:26
msgid ""
"`register_natives` registers fifteen natives with `register_native_closure`, "
"the captured-state route of Chapter 33."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:28
msgid ""
"The host allocates a zeroed shared-data buffer of `vm.shared_data_bytes()` "
"bytes and lends it to the script at each call; the script reads and writes "
"it directly. A host that needs to inspect the segment from Rust has "
"`vm.get_shared`/`vm.set_shared` for per-field scalar access and "
"`vm.marshal_shared_into`/`vm.unmarshal_shared` for whole-segment round-trip "
"against a host struct that mirrors the segment and derives `KeleusmaType` "
"(B34); the piano roll needs neither."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:35
msgid ""
"The main tick loop calls `resume_with_shared`, matches `VmState`, and "
"handles the `Reset` case, the protocol of Chapter 34."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:37
msgid ""
"The `Reset` arm calls `replace_module` (with empty private data) to swap "
"songs and re-sizes the shared buffer, the hot swap of Chapter 37."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:40
msgid ""
"The audio-synthesis code is everything else, and it is not about Keleusma at "
"all. The `Mixer`, the `AudioCallback` implementation, `advance_envelope`, "
"`waveform_sample`, the `Voice` and `EnvState` structs, and the SDL3 device "
"setup are an ordinary software synthesizer. Any audio program would need "
"code like it. When reading the file to learn embedding, this code can be "
"skimmed."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:47 src/PIANO_ROLL.md:87
msgid "The main and run split"
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:49
msgid ""
"The file separates two concerns. The function `main` carries application "
"chrome: argument handling and process-level setup. The function `run` "
"carries the embeddable host loop: build the VM, open the audio device, "
"register natives, drive the tick-and-yield cycle. The boundary between them "
"is the boundary between what a different application would discard and what "
"it would copy. A developer lifting the piano roll into another program "
"copies the body of `run`."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:57
msgid "Patterns from the cookbook"
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:59
msgid ""
"The repository's `COOKBOOK.md` collects host-side patterns that recur across "
"applications and that the piano roll touches: sizing the arena from a "
"module's WCMU, a data-loader pattern for host configuration, narrow-runtime "
"type aliasing for sub-64-bit targets, signed bytecode distribution, and "
"calibrated WCET with a measured cost model. Each is a short recipe building "
"on a technique from this part."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:68
msgid ""
"The piano roll host is one readable file of roughly thirteen hundred lines."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:70
msgid ""
"It contains embedding code and audio-synthesis code; only the first is about "
"Keleusma, and it is a small fraction of the file."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:72
msgid ""
"Every technique of this part appears in it: construction, native "
"registration, the resume protocol, hot swap."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:74
msgid ""
"The `main` and `run` split separates application chrome from the embeddable "
"host loop."
msgstr ""

#: src/39_full_host.md:77
msgid ""
"That completes Part IX. You have the full host-side surface: construction, "
"native functions, the coroutine protocol, arena sizing, bytecode loading, "
"hot swap, and cost models. The final part points to where to go next."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:1
msgid "Chapter 40. Further Reading"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:3
msgid "This is the final chapter of the guide."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:7
msgid "This chapter closes the guide and points to where to go next."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:9
msgid "What you have done"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:11
msgid ""
"Parts I through VIII taught the Keleusma language: its values and types, its "
"functions and control flow, its data shapes, the three function categories "
"and the host conversation, the verifier and the guarantees, the deeper "
"features, how a program is shipped, and the piano roll as a working "
"capstone. Part IX taught the other side, embedding Keleusma in a Rust host. "
"Between them, the guide has covered the whole of what a Keleusma developer, "
"on either side, needs to begin."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:19
msgid "What follows is where to deepen that knowledge."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:21
msgid "A second worked example: the roguelike"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:23
msgid ""
"The piano roll is one worked example. The repository carries a second, "
"larger one: a roguelike game, in `examples/rogue/`, with its long-form "
"manual at `docs/guide/ROGUE.md`. Where the piano roll has one `loop` script, "
"the roguelike is driven by a roster of scripts: a game-tick loop, a dungeon "
"generator, a set of monster behaviors, combat math, and item effects. It is "
"the example to study for how a larger application divides its logic across "
"many Keleusma scripts behind one Rust host."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:31
msgid "The reference documents"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:33
msgid ""
"The guide explained the language. For precise lookup, the repository's `docs/"
"spec/` directory holds the authoritative specifications: the formal grammar, "
"the type system, the standard library, the instruction set, and the wire "
"format. The `docs/architecture/` directory holds the narrative descriptions "
"of the design: `LANGUAGE_DESIGN.md` for the design goals and guarantees, and "
"`EXECUTION_MODEL.md` for the runtime model. When a question needs an exact "
"answer rather than an explanation, these are the documents to open."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:42
msgid "Host-side and troubleshooting references"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:44
msgid ""
"For embedding work beyond Part IX, `docs/guide/COOKBOOK.md` collects host-"
"side recipes, and `docs/guide/EMBEDDING.md` is the full host-facing "
"reference. When the verifier rejects a program, `docs/guide/WHY_REJECTED.md` "
"maps the rejection messages to their causes and rewrites. `docs/guide/"
"FAQ.md` collects the rough edges and surprises that early users meet. The "
"`docs/reference/` directory holds a glossary of terms and `RELATED_WORK.md`, "
"which places Keleusma against the academic and industrial work it draws on."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:53
msgid "The wider repository"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:55
msgid ""
"The `examples/` directory holds smaller programs, each demonstrating one "
"embedding technique. The `examples/rtos/` directory holds a cooperative real-"
"time microkernel that runs Keleusma on embedded hardware, the clearest "
"demonstration of the language's intended deployment target."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:60 src/PIANO_ROLL.md:183
msgid "Closing"
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:62
msgid ""
"Keleusma is a small language, deliberately. It leaves out a great deal so "
"that it can promise a little with certainty: that a program will keep its "
"beat, within a known budget of time and memory, every cycle, forever. "
"Everything in this guide followed from that promise. A program written "
"inside it can be trusted in places an ordinary program cannot."
msgstr ""

#: src/40_further_reading.md:68
msgid "That is the end of the guide. The next step is to write something."
msgstr ""

